<body>
    <!-- Recipe Title and Subtitle -->
    <h1>Fish Amok (Amok Trey)</h1>
    <h2>Cambodia’s National Dish</h2>

    <!-- Photo of the Dish -->
    <img src="fish amok.jpg" alt="Traditional Khmer Fish Amok served in banana leaves" width="400">

    <!-- Ingredients List -->
    <h3>Ingredients</h3>
    <ul>
        <li>500g white fish fillets (catfish or tilapia)</li>
        <li>2 cups coconut milk</li>
        <li>2 tbsp fish sauce</li>
        <li>2 tbsp palm sugar</li>
        <li>2 eggs</li>
        <li>2 tbsp Khmer curry paste (kroeung)</li>
        <li>Banana leaves (for steaming cups)</li>
        <li>Fresh kaffir lime leaves, thinly sliced</li>
        <li>Red chili slices (for garnish)</li>
        <li>Steamed jasmine rice (to serve)</li>
    </ul>

    <!-- Steps -->
    <h3>Instructions</h3>
    <ol>
        <li>Prepare banana leaf cups by folding and securing with toothpicks.</li>
        <li>Cut fish fillets into bite-sized pieces.</li>
        <li>In a bowl, mix coconut milk, curry paste, fish sauce, palm sugar, and eggs until smooth.</li>
        <li>Add fish pieces into the mixture and stir well.</li>
        <li>Spoon the mixture into banana leaf cups.</li>
        <li>Steam for 20–25 minutes until the custard is set and fish is cooked.</li>
        <li>Garnish with kaffir lime leaves and red chili slices.</li>
        <li>Serve hot with steamed jasmine rice.</li>
    </ol>

